definitions: not subject to constraints, limits, or restrictions in behavior or expression
examples: The artist worked with unconstrained creativity on the new project
Children showed unconstrained joy at the surprise party

definitions: not disputed, challenged, or opposed by anyone in competition or argument
examples: She won the uncontested election with no opponents
The team's victory was uncontested after their dominant performance

definitions: not able to be controlled, restrained, or kept in check by will or effort
examples: The child burst into uncontrollable laughter during the show
The wildfire became uncontrollable in the strong winds

definitions: not controlled, regulated, or restrained; happening without deliberate management or restriction
examples: The uncontrolled growth of weeds ruined the garden
His uncontrolled anger caused problems at work

definitions: not giving rise to public disagreement, debate, or dispute; generally accepted
examples: The committee made an uncontroversial decision about the budget
Her appointment was uncontroversial among board members

definitions: not based on or conforming to what is generally done or believed; different from usual practices
examples: She took an unconventional approach to solving the problem
The artist's unconventional style attracted many admirers

definitions: not persuaded to believe something; remaining doubtful or skeptical about a claim
examples: The jury remained unconvinced by the defendant's testimony
She was unconvinced that the plan would work

definitions: failing to make someone believe that something is true or valid; not persuasive
examples: His excuse for being late was unconvincing
The actor gave an unconvincing performance in the role

definitions: not cooked; in a raw state without being heated or prepared
examples: The sushi contains uncooked fish and vegetables
Eating uncooked meat can be dangerous to health

definitions: unwilling to help others or do what they ask; not working together helpfully
examples: The witness was uncooperative during the police investigation
Her uncooperative attitude made the project difficult

definitions: lacking the ability to move different parts of the body together smoothly and efficiently
not organized or arranged to work together effectively as a unified system
examples: The puppy's uncoordinated movements made everyone laugh
His uncoordinated attempts at dancing were endearing
The rescue effort was uncoordinated between different agencies
Their uncoordinated marketing campaigns confused customers

definitions: having no correlation or statistical relationship between two or more variables or sets of data
examples: The study found that happiness and wealth were uncorrelated
These two market trends appear to be completely uncorrelated

definitions: lacking good manners, refinement, or grace; awkward and uncultivated in appearance or behavior
examples: His uncouth behavior at dinner embarrassed his date
The tourists made uncouth remarks about local customs

definitions: not covered by clothing, a roof, or other covering; exposed to view
discovered or revealed after being hidden or unknown; brought to light
examples: She left the food uncovered on the counter
The uncovered pool collected leaves all autumn
The investigation uncovered evidence of fraud
Archaeologists uncovered ancient ruins beneath the city

definitions: not expressing criticism or careful judgment; accepting without analysis or skeptical evaluation
examples: The newspaper gave uncritical coverage of the politician
Her uncritical acceptance of the theory proved problematic

definitions: not prepared and used for growing crops; left in a natural wild state
lacking education, culture, or refinement in behavior and tastes; unsophisticated
examples: The uncultivated land was covered with wild grasses
They bought uncultivated acreage to build their farm
His uncultivated manners shocked the dinner guests
She had natural talent but an uncultivated artistic sense

definitions: not cut with a blade or tool; left in its whole original form
not shortened or edited; presented in complete original version without censorship
examples: The jeweler showed them uncut diamonds from the mine
The grass remained uncut throughout the summer
The director released an uncut version of the film
They published the uncut interview transcript online

definitions: not harmed or injured; remaining in perfect condition without any damage
examples: The package arrived completely undamaged despite rough handling
The car remained undamaged after the minor accident

definitions: not having a date written or printed on it; lacking chronological identification
examples: She found an undated letter in the attic
The undated photograph could be from any decade

definitions: not intimidated or discouraged by difficulty, danger, or disappointment; courageously resolute
examples: She remained undaunted by the challenging climb ahead
The team was undaunted after their early setback

definitions: not having made a decision; unable to make up one's mind about something
not yet settled or resolved; still open to different outcomes or possibilities
examples: Many voters remain undecided about the candidates
She's undecided between studying medicine or law
The outcome of the match is still undecided
The court case remains undecided after months

definitions: not publicly announced, admitted, or made known officially; kept secret
not declared to customs or tax authorities as required by law or regulation
examples: The country waged an undeclared war for years
She harbored undeclared feelings for her colleague
Travelers faced fines for undeclared items at customs
The company hid undeclared income from auditors

definitions: not decorated; plain and simple without ornamental additions or embellishments
examples: The room's undecorated walls gave it a minimalist feel
She preferred undecorated pottery to painted pieces

definitions: not defeated in any contest or battle; having a record of only wins
examples: The team finished the season completely undefeated
The boxer remained undefeated throughout her career

definitions: not defended or protected against attack; left vulnerable without guards or barriers
examples: The undefended border was easy to cross illegally
Their undefended goal allowed the opponent to score

definitions: not clearly or precisely described, stated, or explained; vague in meaning
lacking clear or precise boundaries, limits, or distinctions; indefinite in extent
examples: The project goals remained undefined and confusing
Her role in the company was largely undefined
The border between the countries is still undefined
The painting had undefined edges that blended together

definitions: not relating to or supporting democracy or its principles of equality and fair representation
examples: The committee's undemocratic decision angered many members
Critics called the new voting rules undemocratic

definitions: unable to be denied or disputed; clearly true and impossible to contradict
examples: The evidence of climate change is now undeniable
Her talent as a musician was absolutely undeniable

definitions: below the age required by law for a particular activity or responsibility
examples: The bar refused entry to underage customers
Police caught several underage drivers without licenses

definitions: relating to or located in the area under the arm where it joins the body
thrown or bowled with the hand kept below shoulder level in sports
examples: She applied underarm deodorant before leaving home
The doctor examined the underarm lymph nodes
The child threw an underarm pitch in softball
Underarm bowling was banned in cricket matches

definitions: working secretly using a disguised identity, especially for police investigation purposes
examples: The undercover officer infiltrated the criminal organization
She worked undercover for months gathering evidence

definitions: not fully grown or developed; immature or inadequately formed physically
having a low level of economic development and industrialization compared to other regions
examples: The x-ray showed underdeveloped bones in the child
His underdeveloped muscles needed physical therapy
Many underdeveloped nations struggle with poverty
The underdeveloped region lacked basic infrastructure

definitions: situated, occurring, or operating below the surface of the ground
operating in secret, especially as an alternative to official or mainstream activities
examples: The city built an underground parking garage
Miners work in dangerous underground conditions
The underground resistance movement fought the regime
Underground artists created work outside mainstream galleries

definitions: acting or done in a secret or dishonest way; using unfair methods
examples: His underhand tactics to win the contract upset competitors
They discovered underhand dealings in the company accounts

definitions: done in a secret and dishonest manner; deceitful and not straightforward
examples: The politician used underhanded methods to discredit opponents
Her underhanded scheme eventually came to light

definitions: not enjoying the same standard of living or rights as the majority due to poverty
examples: The charity provides education for underprivileged children
Underprivileged communities often lack access to healthcare

definitions: situated, occurring, or used below the surface of the sea or ocean
examples: Scientists discovered new undersea volcanic activity
The undersea cable carries internet data between continents

definitions: smaller than the usual, standard, or expected size for something
examples: The undersized apartment could barely fit their furniture
Undersized fish must be thrown back into the water

definitions: having fewer staff than necessary to operate effectively or meet demand
examples: The understaffed hospital struggled during the emergency
Many restaurants are understaffed and service suffers

definitions: able to be understood; clear enough in meaning to comprehend easily
natural, reasonable, or forgivable under the circumstances; easy to sympathize with
examples: The instructions were clear and easily understandable
She spoke in simple, understandable language
Your anger about the situation is completely understandable
It's understandable that he needs time to grieve

definitions: presented or expressed in a subtle and effective way without showiness or exaggeration
examples: Her understated elegance impressed everyone at the gala
The room's understated decor created a calming atmosphere

definitions: perceived the meaning of; comprehended or grasped mentally what was communicated
agreed upon or accepted without being openly expressed; implied or assumed
examples: The complex theory was finally understood by students
She understood the instructions after careful reading
There was an understood agreement between old friends
The understood rules of conduct kept order

definitions: situated, occurring, or done beneath the surface of water
having negative equity; owing more on something than its current market value
examples: Divers explored the underwater cave system carefully
The underwater camera captured amazing sea life
Many homeowners found themselves underwater after the crash
The business is underwater with mounting debts

definitions: having started and currently in progress; happening or being done now
examples: Construction of the new bridge is already underway
Plans for the festival are well underway

definitions: weighing less than is normal, healthy, or required for one's age and height
examples: The doctor said the child was slightly underweight
Underweight models face health risks from extreme dieting

definitions: not wanted or desired; likely to cause harm or have bad effects
examples: The medication had undesirable side effects for patients
They removed undesirable elements from the neighborhood

definitions: not wanted or wished for; happening without being intended or sought
examples: The experiment produced undesired results requiring revision
His undesired advances made her uncomfortable

definitions: not able to be discovered or noticed; impossible to detect with available methods
examples: The virus remained undetectable in early blood tests
Modern stealth aircraft are nearly undetectable by radar

definitions: not discovered or noticed; having escaped observation or identification despite being present
examples: The error went undetected for several months
The spy remained undetected throughout the mission
